### What are Pipes?

Pipes transform data in templates. They accept input values and return formatted output without modifying the source data. Angular provides many built-in pipes and allows custom pipes.

### Syntax

```html
{{ expression | pipeName[:param1[:param2...]] }}
```

### Built-in Pipes

**DatePipe** â€” Formats dates:
```html
{{ today | date:'fullDate' }}
<!-- Output: Wednesday, January 12, 2025 -->

{{ today | date:'short' }}
<!-- Output: 1/12/25, 12:00 PM -->

{{ today | date:'yyyy-MM-dd' }}
<!-- Output: 2025-01-12 -->
```

**UpperCasePipe / LowerCasePipe** â€” Transform text case:
```html
{{ 'hello world' | uppercase }}
<!-- Output: HELLO WORLD -->

{{ 'HELLO WORLD' | lowercase }}
<!-- Output: hello world -->

{{ 'hello' | titlecase }}
<!-- Output: Hello -->
```

**CurrencyPipe** â€” Formats numbers as currency:
```html
{{ 42.99 | currency:'USD':'symbol':'1.2-2' }}
<!-- Output: $42.99 -->

{{ 42.99 | currency:'EUR':'symbol':'1.2-2' }}
<!-- Output: â‚¬42.99 -->
```

**PercentPipe** â€” Formats as percentage:
```html
{{ 0.25 | percent }}
<!-- Output: 25% -->

{{ 0.1234 | percent:'1.1-2' }}
<!-- Output: 12.3% -->
```

**JsonPipe** â€” Outputs object as JSON string (useful for debugging):
```html
<pre>{{ user | json }}</pre>
```

### Chaining Pipes

Pipes can be combined by chaining:
```html
{{ birthday | date:'fullDate' | uppercase }}
```

### Locale Formatting

Angular uses the `LOCALE_ID` token for locale-specific formatting:
```typescript
// app.module.ts
import { LOCALE_ID } from '@angular/core';
import localeFr from '@angular/common/locales/fr';
import { registerLocaleData } from '@angular/common';

registerLocaleData(localeFr);

@NgModule({
  providers: [{ provide: LOCALE_ID, useValue: 'fr-FR' }]
})
```

Now `{{ 42.99 | currency:'EUR' }}` outputs `42,99 â‚¬`.

